data.title: One of the most popular TV series of all time is streaming on Netflix this weekend
data.meta_description: The full season of Grey's Anatomy will finally land on Netflix this weekend.
data.text:
After debuting in 2005, and premiering over 430 episodes, Grey’s Anatomy will finally air its landmark 20th season on Netflix.

The long-running ABC medical drama has garnered a cult following of loyal fans who are invested in the lives of doctors and interns at the Grey Sloan Memorial Hospital.

Following the emotional season 19 finale, viewers will finally be able to catch up with the dramas in the absence of Meredith Grey (played by Ellen Pompeo).

The two-hour episode ended with a cliffhanger for almost every character to have a major storyline in the upcoming instalment.

Including Teddy Altman’s (Kim Raver) fate after she shockingly collapsed hours after complaining about a toothache.

Due to being busy at the hospital, she couldn’t get it checked out in time and in the final moments of the episode Mika Yasuda (Midori Francis) could be seen reviving Teddy.

The interns’ residency at the hospital is also under threat after a major rule break saw Lucas (Nico Terho) and Simone (Alexis Floyd) performing surgery without attending supervision.

Kwan (Harry Shum Jr) also broke major protocol when he decided to resuscitate Max (Juliet Mills) despite her do-not-resuscitate order.

However, Netflix streamers will have to wait and see if this trio will join the list of characters who were fired from Grey Sloan.

The season 19 finale also came to a happy end for Dr Bailey (Chandra Wilson) after she won The Catherine Fox Award.

She became the first winner in history who hadn’t been nominated and was winning for a non-surgical achievement.

It was a welcomed surprise as she travelled to Boston with the nominees and under the guise that she was presenting an award.

Although Grey said goodbye early in season 19, she made sporadic appearances throughout the show and will continue to do so in season 20.
